8 election numbers that show Donald Trump in real light
Some have tried to label him as someone who often changes his mind.
The others waved at it as if it were a joke.
And some are preparing to implode.
But as much as some Republicans are trying to pull Donald Trump down from the top of the polls, they&#39;re not succeeding (so far).
10 of the last 11 national polls show Donald Trump leading by double digits, and some people are beginning to seriously question what that means for the real estate mogul&#39;s nomination chances.
Of course, it&#39;s still early in the election cycle.
None of this is to say that Trump is likely to win the Republican nomination.
Experts point out that at this time in 2011, Rick Perry&#39;s leadership paved the way for Herman Cain&#39;s rise, with neither of them winning a single position in the nomination process.
There are many reasons why he could stumble in the general election.
But outside groups like Jeb Bush&#39;s Super PAC and the economic conservative group Club for Growth are realizing Trump&#39;s will to endure and are beginning to pour their dollars into the standoff with the goal of bringing him down.
Here are some recent poll numbers that suggest the real estate mogul isn&#39;t just a passing phase:
Trump&#39;s approval rating has turned 180 degrees.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, a Monmouth University poll showed only two in 10 Republicans had a positive view of the real estate mogul.
By mid-July, it was already 40 percent.
At the beginning of August, it was 52 percent.
Now, six in 10 Republicans have a favorable view of Donald Trump.
About three in 10 say they have a negative opinion of him.
And those numbers are holding up in the early stages.
A Quinnipiac University poll last week found that 60 percent of Republicans had a favorable opinion of Trump.
Two-thirds of GOP voters would be happy with Trump as the nominee.
In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would be either &quot;excited&quot; or &quot;satisfied&quot; with Trump as the nominee.
Only two in 10 said they would be &quot;outraged&quot; by his candidacy.
Only Ben Carson generates roughly the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent of people said they would be &quot;thrilled&quot; versus 40 percent who say the same about Trump).
Next closest in level of excitement?
Marco Rubio with only 21 percent.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republican voters say they would be &quot;dissatisfied&quot; or &quot;upset&quot; if establishment favorite Jeb Bush became the nominee.
Most Republicans don&#39;t see Trump&#39;s temperament as a problem.
While Donald Trump has been widely criticized for his bluster and insults, 52 percent of Republican voters nationwide think the real estate mogul has the right temperament for the presidency, according to an ABC News/Washington Post poll Monday.
The same number holds in the Iowa caucus, which ranks first in the nation, where 52 percent of Republicans think he has a commanding personality, according to Quinnipiac last week.
Still, 44 percent think he doesn&#39;t have the personality to serve effectively, and nearly 6 in 10 independents say his temperament doesn&#39;t belong in the White House, according to ABC/Post.
Republican voters are getting used to the idea.
When they put on their scholarly hats, Republican voters think Trump is the real candidate.
Asked who is most likely to win the GOP nomination, four in 10 said Trump would be the best choice, according to a CNN/ORC poll last week.
That&#39;s a change from late July, when four in 10 were betting their money on Jeb Bush.
Full disclosure: GOP voters haven&#39;t had the clearest crystal ball in the past.
This time in the last cycle, 4 in 10 Republicans chose Rick Perry as the winner of the nomination versus 28 percent for the eventual nomination of Mitt Romney.
Still, it appears that a certain number of GOP voters see the Trump campaign as credible.
Even with Republicans rallying around another candidate, Trump is still beating almost everyone.
Some pundits point out that the fragmented field likely contributes to Trump&#39;s lead, while anti-Trump support is diffused among more than a dozen other candidates.
But a Monmouth University poll from early September shows that in a hypothetical head-to-head matchup between Trump and most of the other Republican candidates, Trump would almost always win majority support.
She leads Carly Fiorina by 13 points, Marco Rubio by 14 points, Walker by 15 points, Jeb Bush by 19 points and finally Rand Paul, John Kasich, Chris Christie by 33 points each.
He&#39;s in a dead heat with Ted Cruz.
The only candidate to beat him?
Ben Carson would lead the businessman by a wide 19 points in a hypothetical one-on-one matchup.
The vast majority of Donald Trump&#39;s supporters say they have already made up their minds.
A new CBS/NYT poll on Tuesday shows that just over half of voters who support Trump say they won&#39;t change their minds.
Obviously, a lot of things can change that, and no one can really say they&#39;ve never changed their mind.
46 percent say they are keeping the back door open for a switch between candidates.
Still, Trump&#39;s current strongest opponent is fellow outsider neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who see their opinion as final would be twice as likely to vote for Trump.
6 in 10 Republicans reportedly agree with Trump on immigration.
Even since Donald Trump called immigrants from Mexico &quot;thugs&quot; in his campaign announcement speech, immigration has remained front and center in the conversation for 2016.
Some worry that Trump&#39;s bluster will lure key Hispanic voters away from the GOP and damage rebranding efforts.
But according to a new ABC/Post poll Monday, six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
It seems that as long as immigration remains in the spotlight, so will Donald Trump.
Frustration with government reaches new highs.
Donald Trump and Ben Carson receive about half the support of Republican voters today, largely because of their outsider status.
Six in 10 Republicans in a new ABC/Post poll Monday say they prefer a political outsider to someone with government experience.
And they&#39;re also very angry with Washington.
A Des Moines Register/Bloomberg Iowa poll a few weeks ago found that three out of four Iowa Republicans are frustrated with Republicans in Congress, with 54 percent &quot;dissatisfied&quot; and 21 percent &quot;pissed off.&quot;
