Jeremy Corbyn to debut on Prime Minister&#39;s Questions
Mr Corbyn&#39;s debut at PMQs has been eagerly awaited since his election
New Labor leader Jeremy Corbyn will make his debut on Prime Minister&#39;s Questions later, and will work with David Cameron for the first time.
Mr Corbyn will ask the first of his six allotted questions shortly after midday, while his performance is likely to be closely scrutinized by the media and MPs.
In a weekly statement, he asked for &quot;less theater and more facts.&quot;
He also stated that he might skip a few sessions, which he would leave to his colleagues.
The meeting will be the first parliamentary test of Mr Corby&#39;s leadership, coming after his appointment to the shadow cabinet and his speech to the TUC&#39;s annual congress on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labor leader&#39;s decision to stand in silence during the national anthem at a service to mark the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain on Tuesday has drawn criticism from a number of Tory MPs and is the focus of several newspaper front-page stories.
Mr Corbyn&#39;s decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
A spokesman for Mr Corbyn said he would &quot;stand in respectful silence&quot; and acknowledge &quot;the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain.&quot;
However, a member of Mr Corbyn&#39;s shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told BBC Two&#39;s Newsnight program that he would advise the Labor leader to sing the national anthem &quot;regardless&quot; of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Almost a dozen shadow ministers refused to serve in Mr Corbyn&#39;s top team, citing differences on the economy, defense and foreign affairs, and just under a sixth of the parliamentary party initially backed him as leader.
The BBC&#39;s political correspondent Robin Brant says political differences at Labor are also &quot;accumulating&quot; following Mr Corbyn&#39;s appointment over his position in the European Union and the government&#39;s benefit cap.
Mr Corbyl told the TUC conference that the Labor Party was putting forward amended proposals to remove the whole idea of a benefit cap.
Hours later Mr Smith, the shadow work and pensions secretary, said the party had &quot;very clearly&quot; opposed the government&#39;s plans to cut the limit from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labor leader to face David Cameron in the decade since he was elected Conservative leader.
The Labor leader, who has promised a different approach to politics, says he has &quot;crowdsourced&quot; ideas for questions for Mr Cameron and has received more than 30,000 suggestions.
The Islington North MP says PMQs are too confrontational and will refrain from both &quot;quick answers&quot; and back-and-forth trade, promising instead to focus on important issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges facing young people.
Mr Corbyn says Angela Eagle, the shadow business secretary, will stand in for him at PMQs when he is not attending — such as when Mr Cameron travels abroad.
He also dropped the idea of having other peers step in for him from time to time, saying he had yet to discuss the matter with House Speaker John Bercow.
When Mr Cameron became leader in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the &quot;Punch and Judy&quot; style of politics often associated with PMQs, but admitted years later that he had failed.
Since its first broadcast in 1990, PMQs have been seen as a key barometer of the judgment of leaders, their conduct of the House and their standing among other MPs, although critics have argued that they have become a caricature and far-reaching reforms are needed.
