What we don&#39;t know is how much time it will take and how long it will last.
For the economy specifically, the history of the small originator offers about timing.
The recession came 11 months after the first rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve in raising rates is often, though not always, a determinant of how the economy and financial assets will respond.
That&#39;s why Fed officials have emphasized so strongly that investors shouldn&#39;t be focused on when rate hikes will begin, but rather the trajectory of how long normalization will take.
There really are more variables at play.
However, at the end of the day, market members may be convinced that all the hype about speed increases may be overblown.
&quot;The Fed&#39;s first hike since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as the end of the era of &#39;cheap money,&#39;&quot; Julian Jessop, chief global economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more mainstream but still low levels to create the seismic shock that many may fear.
This means that there will be adverse effects.
Here&#39;s a look at how some areas of the economy will react, based on historical trends:
Given what the market has seen over the past month or so, the expected rate hike may make the air a bit volatile.
But once the increase occurs, the effect will not be as dramatic.
&quot;There appears to be a trend for stocks to stall again 12-24 months after the first hike, again possibly reflecting a delay in monetary policy,&quot; Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after the Fed hikes.
More specifically, over the past 35 years or so, the market has often gone the most - about 14 percent - into rate hikes in relatively flat 250 days (an average increase of 2.6 percent), and then returns to normal again after 500 days, with an average with a six-cycle return of 14.4 percent, according to a recent Barron&#39;s analysis by Bob Doll, chief equity strategist at Nuveen Asset Management.
Deutsche said the impact on stocks tends to become more pronounced later in the rate hike cycle and the return begins to diminish.
Recession is a fact of economic life, but rate hikes often help it along.
The Fed is currently facing some unprecedented conditions that could precipitate a recession.
Most notably, gross domestic product near its lowest point in history as the Fed raises rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, during the 118 rate hikes since 1950, only twice was nominal year-on-year GDP growth below 4.5 percent.
Even though it was 3.6 percent in the second quarter of 2015, few expect it to be sustained when it was just 1.5 percent in the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising rates against this difficult economic backdrop could be risky, and the question could be &quot;whether this time is different,&quot; Deutsche said.
Market participants have been braced for Fed hikes all year, with all eyes on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week and ending on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve a hike at this meeting, futures trading indicates just a 25 percent chance.
&quot;In our study since 1950, all the leverage cycles to date have been in a super-cycle of leveraging, with GDP masking the early recession peaks very quickly after the incipient recovery,&quot; the report says.
On the contrary, this was clearly a slow recovery from the worst of the recession in the sample period.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, we are now at 74 months and counting.
Fixed income has also been volatile as the market anticipates rate hikes and the pattern is somewhat similar to what equities are experiencing.
The main difference is that the impact is seen more quickly in bonds than in stocks when the Fed changes policy direction.
For bonds, yields seem to change direction immediately after the first arrival of a bull/bear cycle.
At the end of a bullish cycle, bond yields fall immediately,&quot; Deutsche said.
Charles Schwab strategists believe the rate hike will cause yields between long- and short-dated bonds to converge, flattening the curve.
High-yield bonds often do better in this climate, although &quot;we&#39;re still cautious about the yield squeeze,&quot; Kathy Jones, fixed income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
