Multiple sclerosis: it&#39;s not only the drugs that matter, but also the patient&#39;s will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: neurologist, physiotherapist, occupational therapist, urologist, ophthalmologist, psychologist, psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not just about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations if they decide to have a child, the care of these patients also includes social and legal advice, recommendations for housing modifications, etc.
Nevertheless, all this is not enough: the development of the disease can be fundamentally influenced by the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and does not have to fundamentally change his lifestyle.
As doctors point out, the passivity of the sick makes room for the activity of the disease.
For example, it is proven that regular movement significantly delays the time when the patient needs a compensatory aid, such as a cane.
It is important that patients and those around them do not succumb to various myths, for example that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
This is also why the website Dej si schanci (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Dej si schanci.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is the neurologist.
With multiple sclerosis, the adage that the earlier the disease is treated, the more likely the doctor can influence something, is true twice.
This is because we have drugs for multiple sclerosis in the inflammatory stage, when the neurodegeneration process is not yet as strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the hope that we will be able to stop the disease and delay invalidation, explains MUDr. Eva Medová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
Rehabilitation care is very important for people with multiple sclerosis, which most often solves the weakening of the lower limbs or balance disorders.
We work with patients according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, alleviate swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
&quot;It&#39;s really individual, it depends on the specific problems of the patient,&quot; says MUDr. Martina Kövári, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Education Medicine at the Faculty Hospital in Motola.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it manifests itself in a slightly different way for everyone.
Rehabilitation cannot stop the disease, but it can always alleviate its symptoms.
Physical activity, however, also strengthens the body&#39;s immune status, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive of regular exercise is the fact that patients check what they can do, and this strengthens their self-confidence.
&quot;During exercise, endorphins also flow out and you feel good after it,&quot; points out PhDr. Kamila Řasová from the Department of Rehabilitation Medicine of the University Hospital of Královská Vinohrady.
By affecting the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
In this way, we directly intervene in the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, he adds.
&quot;Previously, these patients so-called sparing themselves, today we know that they need targeted exercise,&quot; says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Education Medicine, University Hospital in Motol.
The goal of physiotherapy is to enable a person to remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including employment.
Physiotherapists therefore work together with occupational therapists so that each person receives a compensatory aid tailored to him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They are in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, it shakes most people.
They experience shock, panic, fear.
They have to react to a heavy load - loss of health.
With such a sore soul, we should go to someone, not try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
&quot;I work with them so that they finally come to the conclusion that even with a handicap you can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life,&quot; says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
Airbuses would not fly without the Prague manufacturer Latecoere.
Aerospace manufacturing is synonymous with precision and advanced technology.
New planes are full of titanium or light and strong composite materials that no one can produce and process right away.
Nevertheless, next to super-precise, computer-controlled machine tools, next to autoclaves for shaping composites, you can come across something as ordinary as apricot pits.
In the drum, which resembles a cotton candy pot, the edges of sheet metal parts that have just come out of the milling machine are tumbled in a pile of bricks.
&quot;So far, no one has come up with anything better,&quot; smiles Ivan Dubský, CEO of aircraft door manufacturer Latecoere Czech Republic.
The former Letov manufactures complete doors for the Airbus A320 at the site in Prague&#39;s Letňany.
They are the only ones in the world to supply doors for the Brazilian Embraer 170.
Passengers also enter first and higher class on the upper decks of the world&#39;s largest airliner, the Airbus A380, through the doors, part of which is being assembled in Prague.
Composite doors for the new Boeing 787 Dreamliner are also assembled here.
Accuracy is the main motto here.
For example, the company has torque wrenches adjusted twice a year.
If there was no inspection record on the yellow sticker, they would have something to explain to the auditors from Airbus or Boeing at the Prague plant, who come regularly to find out if the doors are manufactured according to the agreed rules.
However, advanced technology has not yet completely replaced human senses.
There are 1500 rivets on one A320 door.
Users have to knock them out manually.
It takes them two days.
Even by the sound of the falling hammer, they can tell if the rivet has already been properly tapped.
The tolerance in which they move is minimal.
The rivet can protrude from zero to 0.13 millimeters above the surface of the aircraft.
That&#39;s roughly twice the thickness of a human hair.
A trained touch comes into play during inspection.
When the inspector runs his finger over a row of rivets, he can tell if any are out of tolerance.
Only then will he pick up an accurate deviation meter.
Before 1989, Letov supported the L-39 military training aircraft program.
But in 1991 not a single one was produced.
The company had to quickly find new orders.
It was then that it teamed up with the European aircraft manufacturer Airbus.
It won the tender for the supplier of emergency doors for the A321 model.
The courtship with Boeing was not so happy.
&quot;At that time, we were a small company that did not have enough money for investments and to be able to guarantee long-term stable deliveries to Boeing,&quot; recalls Dubský.
The door to the American manufacturer would have remained closed if Letov had not attracted the French Latecoere group at the Prague conference of the international association of the aviation industry in 1999.
I spoke there about our cooperation with Airbus.
The next day, negotiations with the French started, says Dubský.
A year later Latecoere bought the Czech company and new orders came with a strong company.
As early as 2000, assembly of door parts for the A320 began.
Three years later, upper deck doors were added for the A380.
In 2006, the company built a new hall for the processing of composites for deliveries for the Boeing Dreamliner.
Without Latecoere, we would not have been able to get these large orders on our own.
Maybe we would make parts or small components.
The partners want supply guarantees for twenty or thirty years, explains Dubský.
Last year, the Czech Latecoere achieved a turnover of over 2.9 billion and a profit after tax of 147 million crowns.
An exclusive position among suppliers of aircraft manufacturers is not free.
Latecoere has invested 1.5 billion crowns in Prague since 2000.
The company must have quality certificates, certification of 170 special production processes and certificates of qualification for key employees.
Without them, the company would not produce any aircraft doors.
According to Dubský, it costs millions of crowns to obtain certificates that production processes meet customer requirements and to maintain them during repeated inspections.
Production processes change every year.
They are more precise and strict.
We have to retrain employees, retrofit equipment and re-certify the entire process, adds Dubský.
Now the company is completing the preparation of the process for plating with zinc and nickel, which will replace the existing cadmium, which is harmful to human health.
Although they received the assignment from the manufacturer, they then had to adapt the technology for the equipment or chemicals they use in Prague.
People from Boeing will come and check the concept of the entire line.
Then we will show them the production.
They will also check our laboratory.
They test one set of samples themselves in their laboratory and then compare the results with ours, Dubský explains the way in which customers check them.
The Prague company is rewarded with long-term exclusive contracts.
Today, the production of embraers stands and falls with the Prague plant.
For the A320, it produces half of the total door volume.
Replacing the Czech Latecoere is either impossible or very difficult for a Brazilian or European manufacturer.
However, this does not mean that he can ask any price for the door.
A price curve is part of the contract.
It indicates how much one door will cost after ten, fifty, or hundreds of manufactured pieces.
The price per piece keeps falling to a certain limit value.
We have to fit into this pricing formula.
If not, we will lose money, says Dubský.
Half of the hall, where electrical cabinets for the Airbus A400 M military aircraft are assembled, is still empty.
However, it is a symbol of the future.
Behind the scenes, a new semi-robotic line for riveting and assembly of doors for the upgraded A320 Neo model is being built here.
Riveting becomes faster and more accurate.
&quot;That&#39;s the trend towards assembly in aviation,&quot; adds Dubský.
Sales of the future line are secured.
Airbus reports that airlines have ordered 3,278 units of the new A320 model so far.
A line for the complete assembly of doors for the upper deck of the A380 will be established just a few meters away.
It is a strategic decision of our parent company.
