Scientists have raised worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change direction when hit by sound pulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
The pulses work by switching genetically modified motor neuron cells that are programmed to respond to these ultrasound waves.
Related: Scientists Can Read and Record Brain Activity Using Light
The researchers said these worms are a great example of a new methodology called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart and muscle cells and activate them outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure in which electrodes are inserted into the patient&#39;s brain to stimulate the brain. The method is used, for example, to treat the symptoms of Parkinson&#39;s disease.
Nematodes don&#39;t normally respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that a response occurred when he placed them in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
As he discovered, the bubbles amplify the ultrasound waves, which then travel through the worms&#39; bodies.
Amplified ultrasound waves act on TRP-4 ion channels, which are found in the membranes of some worm cells.
The sound waves cause these channels to open and activate the cells they are connected to, according to a report in the journal Nature Communications.
To control the nematodes with ultrasound waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contain TRP-4 ion channels.
When he then applied ultrasound to the modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by the microbubbles and transmitted to the worms, where they turned on the modified motor neurons.
The new method is similar in many ways to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light.
But Chalasani let it be known that sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent through an optical fiber to the desired location in the brain, ultrasound waves can penetrate tissue without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
&quot;We believe that by using gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases,&quot; Chalasani said.
He added that the method would also find its application in the treatment of muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
