Apple has hit the yo-yo effect.
The displays are to blame for everything.
A more powerful processor, a camera with a higher resolution, a stronger chassis or a display that recognizes the force of touch, these are the advantages of the recently introduced ninth generation iPhones.
The last two also have a negative impact on the dimensions and weight of the iPhone 6s and 6s Plus.
Apple&#39;s trend so far has been that each new iPhone generation is lighter than the previous one.
The only exceptions were the third and fourth generations, whose weight increased slightly compared to previous iPhones.
At the same time, the two-gram difference in weight to the disadvantage of the new product was really negligible.
However, this is far from the case with the new iPhones.
Compared to last year&#39;s iPhone 6 and 6 Plus, the smaller model&#39;s weight has increased by 14 grams, and the larger one by a full 20 grams.
On the one hand, it is not surprising, last year&#39;s affair with bending in the pockets greatly tormented Apple.
The chassis of the novelties is thus made of a more durable aluminum alloy 7000, which was also reflected in the weight.
But displays have a much greater impact on it.
Apple used 3D Touch technology for the new products, thanks to which the displays recognize the force of touch.
For this, it was necessary to equip the display with an additional layer of capacitive sensors.
The weight of the displays of the new iPhones thus increased more than twice compared to previous generations.
For the smaller iPhone, from originally 12 grams to 29 grams, in the case of the larger one, from 19 to 40 grams.
The display is thus the heaviest component used in the iPhone 6s.
The weight of only 143 grams is also achieved with this new product thanks to the degreasing crust, which touched most of the remaining components.
In the larger model, the heaviest element used is the battery, but its weight has not changed in any way compared to its predecessor.
Even in this case, the biggest increase is noticeable in the display.
The weight of the 5.5&quot; iPhone 6s Plus thus reaches 192 grams.
The extent to which the new display technology will be practical will only become apparent during use.
The first users will be able to try it already on Friday, September 25, when sales of iPhone 6s and 6s Plus will begin in selected countries.
Have cereal been the breakfast of champions for tens of thousands of years?
In Italy&#39;s Grotta Paglicci, archaeologists have made a discovery that opens up interesting possibilities.
They found traces of modern human habitation from various times, including wall paintings, remains of tools and so on and so forth.
However, in layer 23A, which according to the tools is dated to around 30 thousand years ago, scientists discovered something that is very reminiscent of the remains of a breakfast buffet.
Traces of oat grains were found at the site, which apparently went through the production process of today&#39;s popular flakes.
With it, the grains today are first soaked, then dried, stripped of their packaging, the so-called fluff, then steamed and pressed flat.
In the Paglicci cave, grains were found that were apparently heated or boiled, and then apparently crushed between two millstones - at least that is what the traces of use on the two stones in the cave suggest.
So the scientists could not prove in their publication for the journal PNAS that a complete flake-making process took place in the cave, but the similarity is indeed very striking.
We also have no evidence of how people could have eaten the flakes, but the assumption that it was with some liquid and quite possibly warm is of course quite logical.
At the same time, it is a very interesting proof of how intensively people used cereals long before the emergence of agriculture.
If the flake interpretation is correct, the oldest flakes preceded agriculture by about twenty thousand years.
