The symbol of the village came to life.
The wheel of the windmill above Chlum is spinning again after years.
It can be seen from afar because it is placed on a fifteen meter high mast.
People from the wider area call it &quot;the fan on Chlum&quot;.
For the village with 150 inhabitants, it even became one of the elements of the municipal coat of arms, which the village acquired on the occasion of a meeting of natives in 2010.
&quot;At that time, we applied for a logo and of course we wanted to have the fan on the logo, everyone in the neighborhood knows it,&quot; stated Mayor Jiří Mašek.
The Chlum wind pump is a local technical monument.
It is a bit of a memento of the present: it reminds of the time when local people fought for quality drinking water.
It was a rarity in Chlum in past centuries.
It was not until 1910 that the representatives of Chlum decided on a solution that was then satisfactory until the mid-eighties.
They had a seven-meter-deep well dug in the village near the turnoff to Číchov.
Three years later, the well was supplemented with a metal structure with a wind pump, which pumped water into the reservoir at the highest point of the village, near the local church.
&quot;The construction was carried out by the company Antonín Kunc from Hranice in Moravia at a cost of 2,400 crowns,&quot; says the commemorative inscription on the ground floor fence of the mast structure.
The pump reached its end of life in 1971 after several repairs and falling of the windmill.
On May 7, 1973, a new chapter in the fight for water began to be written: on that day, a new water supply system began operating in Chlum.
The wind pump remained only a non-functioning municipal symbol and a local rarity.
The Dominant was put into operation at this year&#39;s gathering of natives.
It wasn&#39;t until 2008 that the Chlums decided to repair the windmill again and put it back into operation.
They had a replica of the original wheel made - reduced in diameter by half a meter.
The bike was mounted on a mast, but it had to be taken down the same year.
The manufacturer of the replica did not choose the appropriate material and the bike could not withstand gusts of wind.
After that, the landmark of Chlum rested for several years, dismantled under the roof.
Since this June, however, the wheel on the tall mast has been turning again.
On the occasion of the meeting of natives, the village had a replica of the wheel modified and re-installed it on the top of the iron tower.
But the wheel pumps service water from the well only to the overflow blind arm.
