When I once managed to live in a block of flats, I soon stopped being the only resident.
Fish have moved into my umakart toilet.
House fishes, insects with an incomplete metamorphosis, i.e., not undergoing the transformation from a caterpillar to a beetle, and the young look like an adult, only they are tiny and gradually grow.
They were disgusting to me and I was not lazy to destroy them.
First manually and later chemically.
The socialist drugstore provided a kind of blue crystals for their liquidation.
I think it was called Zyklon B.
Or some other way?
However, it successfully disposed of them.
Later, I dealt with the pharaohs in a similar way.
A box with some kind of juvenalizer that the ants brought to the nest and then did not allow the queen to generate new offspring.
But I digress.
As time went by, insects also became objects of my admiration and I was more and more inclined to think that they have the same right to life as we humans.
In addition, I learned from life that interfering with the ecosystem does not lead to success and one pest can be replaced by another.
True, with fleas and bedbugs, I probably wouldn&#39;t hesitate to make my karma worse by killing them.
In our new residence, my partner and I agreed that if the fishes don&#39;t climb our necks, let them eat flakes of fallen skin, some invisible algae and the like.
After a while, their peaceful existence was disturbed by a spider.
It was a common species of woodpecker that resided on the ceiling for a long time.
We assumed that he lived off the occasional flies and mosquitoes, which only increased our comfort.
Because he lived with us for several years, we found out that he feeds mainly on fish and that he apparently kept their number at a sustainable level.
Through confidential regular contact with each need performed, we found out that it was a female.
For we have witnessed romantic courtship with a partner about a third smaller, carefully plucking at the threads of the web so as not to be eaten before the desired copulation is achieved.
It lasted for about three days where they did not move and did not even respond to our checks.
We later found the remains of a dried male next to the female under the toilet bowl, where the love games took place.
After that, the spider didn&#39;t move for weeks.
When we thought she was done with it, we were surprised by the number of small spiders hanging around her.
They soon disappeared.
Some of them were eaten by their mother, some of them ran away elsewhere.
Even the female disappeared somewhere after a week.
We don&#39;t know if she went somewhere else or fell asleep, but after a month or two, she reappeared on the ceiling.
True, a little smaller, probably the daughter of the former inhabitant of the toilet.
For some time, she cautiously observed our behavior from the ceiling, and by moving under the toilet bowl, she evaluated our non-attack as friendship.
The numerical status of the fishes, which had increased somewhat, decreased again, and the spider calmly went about its usual activities to secure food.
Our ecosystem hasn&#39;t changed all year.
Meanwhile, our daughter reached an age where using the potty was a shame.
We have tolerated it until now, but the eternal pouring out of its contents has fed us.
We encouraged her more and more strongly to use the toilet.
However, the daughter found an excuse to keep her bad habit in that spider, which she saw very well while wiping.
She didn&#39;t take our talk about seeing a spider and having luck in the house at all.
She forced her potty by crying and yelling.
There was no point.
There came a time when the spider had to surrender, in the interests of the daughter&#39;s development.
It was left to me.
He was caught in a glass and banished over the balcony to somewhere in the garden.
I said goodbye to him as a friend, but still, after living together for so long, I felt disgusting, as if I were throwing out a relative.
We assumed that the fish would start to appear more often and begin to multiply in a geometric series.
It&#39;s amazing, for a week or two, we haven&#39;t seen any of them there.
I began to speculate about the cause.
I wondered if the spider had somehow cultivated them there, following the pattern of ants, that the environment of the toilet was not as favorable for their existence as we thought.
But then the first pieces of medium size appeared, and they swarmed again.
I had to come up with another theory about the cause of their disappearance, and I figured that their attachment to the spider must have been because when they can&#39;t see it, it&#39;s hidden in some other place and they&#39;re in danger from anywhere.
Or, maybe they had some kind of telepathic connection with their predator and its rapid disappearance caused some kind of alarm response.
Especially since I have no illusions about their eyesight.
They showed some light shyness, but not that they would react to waving hands or quick movements.
My daughter already goes to the toilet regularly.
I think she forgot the potty.
All that remains is to attract another spider.
