&quot;We didn&#39;t get an answer, and that&#39;s why we wanted the quotas to be deleted from the final text,&quot; Chovanec told reporters.
Can you more specifically describe the position with which you came to the meeting of the Ministers of the Interior and Foreign Affairs of the European Union?
We do not agree with mandatory quotas as a system that simply cannot work.
We cannot talk about migrants as bags of salt or flour.
They are living beings who have some visions, they are going somewhere, they have some relatives.
We wanted to hear from our colleagues how we are able to keep migrants on the territory of the member states if they were to redistribute themselves.
We can&#39;t imagine it.
We did not receive an answer and therefore wanted the quotas to be removed from the final text.
We have no problem with the other conclusions - functional hotspots, i.e. registration points, border protection, camps outside Europe, a trust fund for African countries and other things.
We&#39;ve been talking about this for a year and we&#39;ve been saying this is the way to go.
But to say that quotas will solve everything?
Not long ago we were dealing with forty thousand, now it is one hundred and twenty thousand.
When will it be five hundred thousand?
And how do we keep those people in that area?
Ninety-eight percent of all people who pass through us want to go to Germany.
Almost no one wants to join us, we simply don&#39;t know how to keep them here.
Other foreigners, Ukrainians, Vietnamese and others who take the Czech Republic as a destination country, have the ambition to come to us, and obtain asylum here, but the interest of people from this wave of migration, i.e. from Syria and other countries, is borderline close to zero.
You mentioned that refugees don&#39;t even want to come to us, but we have already committed to accepting fifteen hundred people.
Wouldn&#39;t it be possible to receive more of them this way?
We undertook to accept 1,500 people, but with a condition.
We said: functional hotspots, border protection, military operation.
Even with the 1,500, the point is that 1,100 people will come, with whom we will handle the asylum procedure.
They will come to our detention facility and we will treat them the same way we treat them.
It is a big question, and we will debate it with Europe, whether we can detain people who will be registered in Italy and Greece, or Hungary.
Because Europe treats it in such a way that if they have a registration, they cannot be detained.
This means that they will come to our territory with registration, and if there is an agreement, which is not yet in place, it may happen that we will not even keep the 1,100 in the territory of the Czech Republic, and they will go to Germany again after their arrival.
If we can detain them for the duration of the asylum procedure, we will complete the asylum procedure with them.
If they are citizens of Syria or Eritrea, almost 98 percent of them receive international protection according to European statistics.
Then they get documents that allow them to travel around Europe.
And I think these people will end up in destination countries again.
Then there are four hundred people who will be relocating.
That&#39;s the second project that&#39;s going on so far, and we&#39;ve only progressed there in that we&#39;re debating with the churches about the possibility of helping them find jobs, housing, and so on.
But that&#39;s a very long shot.
You said that the other states were not willing to discuss with us at the ministerial meeting.
