In their most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week seated at a 27-foot-long Honduran mahogany table, deciding whether, after nearly a decade, the time has come to raise the key interest rate.
Towering above them at one end of the central bank ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are supposed to put the nation&#39;s economic interests above all else.
The central bank has a dual mandate from Congress: to maximize American employment and keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have recognized that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be the X-factor in too close to a predictable decision to be announced Thursday on whether the U.S. economy is ready to launch as it unwinds from the unprecedented stimulus of near-zero short-term interest rates in place since the end of 2008.
Although most data points to solid economic growth, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could spook the already cautious Fed into adding to volatility by raising its benchmark federal funds rate - by as little as a quarter of a percentage point.
&quot;Obviously the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing to watch first and foremost,&quot; said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage Stifel Nicolaus &amp; Co.
&quot;But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to raise rates, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already gives them enough justification to wait further,&quot; she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is causing jitters in financial markets.
About half of economists recently polled by Blomberg expected a rate hike this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to hold off on the matter, with the key indicator only about a 30% chance of a hike.
That would point to a downside for the stock market if the Fed raises rates, only if policymakers soften the plunge by promising that no more hikes are in the offing.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rally was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep rates calm this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody&#39;s Capital Markets Research Group.
&quot;It would be a surprise if the Fed raised rates now,&quot; he says.
If Fed policymakers were to do that, &quot;they would have to go to extremes in their policy statement and hold the financial markets&#39; hands so they don&#39;t panic.&quot;
Other experts said a rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared on track to raise rates by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects to raise rates this year through the spring and early summer, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labor market has seen solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% in the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage gains showed signs of picking up.
And while inflation continues to run below the central bank&#39;s annual 2% target, Fed policymakers say the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy &quot;can handle higher rates and needs them given the tight labor market,&quot; said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to tumble late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell as much as 16% below its record high in May as investors worried that China&#39;s slowing economy would drag down global growth.
The market has rebounded somewhat this month, and the Dow is now only about 10% off its May high.
The unsettled situation on the market provides Fed policymakers with a complex calculation of when to start raising interest rates.
&quot;Absent what happened in the financial markets and reports of weakness in the Chinese economy over the past few weeks, there would have been some tightening at this meeting,&quot; said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former official Fed.
He now predicts they will wait at least a month to get a better handle on the consequences.
&quot;There&#39;s a lot of uncertainty about what impact this is going to have on the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data to go by on the latest developments in China,&quot; Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed&#39;s main concerns, so technically it shouldn&#39;t factor into their decision making.
But in reality the Fed has become the monetary authority of the entire world.
The influence of the central bank in recent years has been enormous.
The mere suggestion by then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might &quot;taper&quot; their monetary expansion in the market set off convulsions around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interconnected, Fed officials can be expected to monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central bankers and experts to better read the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is &quot;more art than science,&quot; said Zachary Karabell, head of global wealth-management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., noted this month that &quot;the Fed has a history of excessive moves in financial markets that seem disconnected from economic fundamentals.&quot;
Lacker, a voting policymaking member of the Federal Open Market Committee that pushed for rate hikes, cited the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to reduce its benchmark rate by 0.75 percentage points during the three sessions &quot;Despite the limited identifiable impact on growth in the US,&quot; said Lacker.
A year later, Fed officials reversed those cuts.
The Fed should prioritize financial stability concerns only during a major crisis like the 2008 market crash, said Adam Posen S., a former member of the Bank of England&#39;s rate-setting committee.
The latest uproar doesn&#39;t even come close to that level, he said.
&quot;You certainly don&#39;t want to be in a situation of fearing a rate hike because the markets got upset,&quot; said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and doesn&#39;t mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don&#39;t think they should come out on top.
