Speed on highways will remain the same.
Acceleration to 150 km/h was rejected by the House of Representatives.
On selected highway sections, it will not be possible to increase the maximum permitted speed to 150 km/h under favorable conditions.
This was the decision of the House of Representatives on Tuesday, when it acceded to an amendment proposed by the Senate, which rejected the speed increase.
The amendment to the Road Traffic Act will now go to the President.
President Miloš Zeman already said at the end of April that he would veto the law allowing a speed of 150 kilometers.
The Minister of Transport Dan Ťok (for ANO) was also against the increase, according to which the Czech highway network is not yet built for such a speed.
Ťok supported the senate version of the law in front of the deputies on Tuesday.
The approved amendment will now allow, in accordance with the original government proposal, an increase in speed from 90 to 110 kilometers per hour on selected first-class roads, especially four-lane roads.
The Chamber of Deputies first extended this option to highways, on which it would be possible to drive at speeds of up to 150 km/h in selected sections, but the Senate rejected it.
The MPs have now accepted his proposal.
The senators, with the consent of the Minister of Transport, also removed from the amendment the authority of the traffic police to have the last word in the modification of local roads, which are taken care of by municipalities.
The Senate version, which was approved by the Chamber of Deputies, also provides for sewage, water pipes or public lighting cables to be laid lengthwise under the road surface.
Municipalities would thus save money on the purchase of land.
Municipalities should also not be required to take care of roadside vegetation along local roads regardless of the owner of the land concerned.
The amendment is also intended to help improve road protection and make it easier for municipalities to deal with towed vehicles whose owners do not report.
Newly, municipalities could sell towed vehicles whose owners do not apply for them within a six-month period after notification of the towing.
Municipalities will be able to exclude transit freight transport through their territory on second and third class roads under the threat of fines for forwarding companies as well.
The amendment also cancels the possibility of introducing electronic highway signs instead of the existing paper ones, which will thus be used even after January 1 next year.
According to the government, this will save money for the introduction of an electronic system.
