For mildly obese diabetics, weight loss surgery could be helpful
The benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes may last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to tell whether mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those given non-surgical treatment.
&quot;Mortality figures take a long time to show,&quot; says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote the editorial for the new JAMA Surgery study.
Weight loss surgery, bariatric surgery uses different methods to shrink the stomach.
Reducing hunger and limiting the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective for treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the research has been done on morbidly obese people with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the ratio of weight to height, is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates a person is overweight, and people with a value above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected from a 2007 study looking at two types of bariatric surgery -- gastric bypass and gastrectomy -- in type 3 diabetes treatments in people who were moderately obese.
The average BMI among those who had the surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who were not given surgical treatment for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among patients with surgery, diabetes was resolved completely in 36 percent and partially in 28 cases.
In the drug-treated group, for comparison, diabetes was completely resolved in only 1 percent and only partially in about 2 percent of patients.
Also, control of blood pressure, triglycerides and &quot;bad&quot; LDL cholesterol was shown to be &quot;generally better in the surgical group,&quot; the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient&#39;s blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects the body&#39;s ongoing blood sugar levels.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, researchers say.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the drug-treated group, this value remained at about 8 percent.
But this better &quot;glycemic control&quot; -- reflected in better hemoglobin A1c levels -- did not reduce mortality at five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results with the two types of surgery.
After five years, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastrectomy group (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), achieved greater decreases in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1), and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent vs. 2.1 percent) and were more likely to have diabetes remission (46.9 percent vs. 16.7 percent).
While the new study does not show an improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden, where they found that surgery leads to longer life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had about a 29 percent greater chance of survival over the next 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not show an improvement in survival among patients after the surgery, Blackstone said this is a reassuring result for people with a BMI under 35 who are interested in these procedures.
&quot;That&#39;s where this work is critical because it shows that surgery is safer in the lower BMI group,&quot; without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone also goes on to say that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously after a patient&#39;s BMI drops between 27 and 30.
&quot;I think we&#39;re waiting too long to let people know the gravity of the situation,&quot; he says.
