The European Union decided on Monday to deal first with the refugee problem: it would rather systematically sort migrants and asylum seekers as soon as they set foot on the old continent - especially in Greece - rather than squabble over the future distribution of refugees according to quotas based on the number that increasingly distant from reality.
Six days after European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker asked 25 of the 28 EU countries to redistribute 160,000 refugees, the interior ministers of the member states changed the priority.
Rather than worrying about the final destination of the refugees, it is first necessary to filter those who arrive today and resolve the fate of those who are already moving within the Schengen area.
&quot;Effective management of the EU&#39;s external borders is essential for managing migration,&quot; the text discussed by ministers on Monday in Brussels emphasizes.
After the single currency crisis, the EU finds itself in jeopardy in its next major integration project.
Germany may be surprised, but they are not losing their resolve and are increasing the pressure.
It restores border controls, especially with Austria, but without blocking the flow of those seeking asylum in that country.
The Central Power thereby makes it clear that without it no free movement in Europe is possible.
The fact that Austria and Slovakia joined this measure on Monday served as proof.
Poland, the Netherlands, Belgium and even France are also considering it, albeit with varying degrees of intensity.
Hungary has been doing this for a long time.
These exceptional and temporary measures are permissible under Schengen rules.
Even a blind person can see that this is a domino effect.
A key issue for Berlin and Paris now is the effective introduction of mandatory entry checks in Greece, southern Italy and also in Hungary for those who have already crossed inland.
French Interior Minister Bernard Cazeneuve and his German counterpart Thomas de Maizière discussed it intensively during a private conversation with their three colleagues from Greece, Italy and Hungary.
This idea is by no means new, but it is implemented rigidly.
In Italy, according to unofficial statistics, two-thirds of the newly arrived refugees have already been registered and identified by fingerprinting.
Budapest refuses to introduce any entry point on its territory, because it fears more than others that it will not be left with camps in which refugees would accumulate at its expense.
Greece remains the real black hole.
More than 200,000 people have landed on its islands near the Turkish coast this year, which is twice as many as have arrived in Italy recently.
Most of them are genuine asylum seekers who came directly from Syria after passing through overcrowded camps in Lebanon, Turkey and Jordan.
It&#39;s a huge gaping hole.
Athens, still in financial disarray and awaiting a new government, folded its hands in its lap.
That is the starting point for the Balkan journey and a source of now shared concern for German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán.
The Juncker Commission promises that checkpoints will be introduced as soon as possible, but has not given a number or a date.
&quot;The challenges faced by Greece apply to the whole of Europe,&quot; the EU interior ministers agreed on Monday to mobilize on this front.
It is therefore a matter of deploying intervention teams of the European border control agency Frontex in this country.
The EU wants to help Greece expand its capacity to receive asylum seekers and strengthen surveillance of the islands.
&quot;It will require adequate financial resources,&quot; warns the text submitted to ministers for approval.
Athens will continue to have the final say in terms of law.
The question of the creation of real European border guards has not been officially raised, but Europe is getting close to it.
The new emergency situation of the 2018 pushed aside the issue of binding quotas and 160,000 refugees, which was already raised at the beginning of the year by the Juncker Commission and the European Parliament and which was strongly supported by Angela Merkel and French President François Hollande.
Hungary, Slovakia, the Czech Republic and Poland still don&#39;t even want to hear about it.
They see it as an attack on their sovereignty.
The number, but not the obligation, was retained on Monday in the text approved by the majority of the twenty-eight.
But as a political commitment.
In other words, the process is aborted.
The only firm promise includes the redistribution of 40,000 refugees over the next two years, which was already agreed in June during a hectic EU summit, Le Figaro concludes.
