In the event of bankruptcy of the CK, insurance companies have to pay the clients&#39; claims in full.
Insurance companies should cover client claims in full in the event of travel agency bankruptcy.
The House of Representatives decided on this on Wednesday, when it approved a revised amendment to the Act on the Conditions of Doing Business in the Tourism Industry.
Travel agencies will be able to replace bankruptcy insurance with a bank guarantee, according to the draft that is headed for consideration by the Senate.
Insurance companies do not agree with the obligation to pay clients&#39; claims even above the agreed limit.
The Ministry for Regional Development insists on the amendment, arguing for consumer protection.
Insurance companies have already threatened to stop insuring travel agencies against bankruptcy if the amendment goes into effect.
However, travel agencies also criticize the proposal.
Without insurance, they will either have to quit or go abroad.
Minister for Regional Development Karla Šlechtová (for ANO) pointed out that cases where insurance companies did not pay full compensation are not Euro-compliant.
She drew attention to this year&#39;s decision of the Constitutional Court, which confirmed that the client is entitled to a full refund regardless of the insurance limit.
Insurance companies will receive enough information about the management of travel agencies and will be able to determine the correct limit, emphasized Šlechtová.
&quot;We appreciate the effort to increase consumer protection, but it must have such a limit that it is feasible,&quot; countered TOP 09 vice-chairman Miroslav Kalousek.
According to him, the bank guarantee will not work because no one will give it unlimited.
&quot;Travel agencies will have to close their operations or move them abroad,&quot; warned Kalousek.
Tomio Okamura (SPD), member of the presidium of the Association of Czech Travel Agencies and Agencies, disagreed with Kalousk&#39;s concerns based on a survey of Central Committee members.
&quot;Stop showing us lobbying insurance companies,&quot; he said.
Okamura does not consider the statements of the insurance companies to be relevant, according to him, there is no official written statement from them in this sense.
However, they are reportedly investigating whether the travel agencies will pay a co-payment, which, according to Okamura, is not a problem.
Jana Fischerová (ODS), who referred to the position of the competing Association of Travel Agencies of the Czech Republic, and her party colleague Petr Bendl, who spoke about the cleaning of the stairs by Czech travel agencies, also warned against the provision.
According to Fischer, travel agencies will not be able to negotiate insurance.
&quot;Consumer protection works,&quot; says Fischerová.
Her proposal to delete the disputed passage was not approved by the House.
Even Vojtěch Filip (KSČM) did not go ahead with the proposal to return the draft to the committee due to the alleged contradiction with the Civil Code.
Filip drew attention to travel agencies that, according to him, can threaten consumers.
The rapporteur of the bill, Martina Berdychová (ANO), has withdrawn her proposal, which would have limited the liability of insurance companies in cases where they could not have known that the insurance payment would not cover the entire risk, due to the verdict of the Constitutional Court.
The amendment will not include the originally proposed minimum four million insurance limit for travel agencies that offer air travel, and the million limit for offices selling, for example, bus tours.
The limit will remain at 30 percent of the planned revenue from tour sales.
However, the insurance indemnity limit will have to be such that it covers all customer claims in the event of the travel agency&#39;s bankruptcy.
Even after the amendments, the standard stipulates that travel agencies will have to indicate which travel agency organizes the tour for the tours they sell.
Travel agencies will have to submit to insurance companies before concluding a contract, among other things, data on finances and the number of trips.
The approved amendment proposal of the Committee for Public Administration also provides for further regular informing of insurance companies.
Travel agencies will have to provide them with data on the number of passengers and sold tours, the total price of sold tours and the amount of advance payments and sales for tours and vouchers.
If the Ministry of Regional Development finds that the travel agency has not fulfilled any of its legal obligations towards the insurance company, it will, according to the draft, call on it to make corrections or it will be able to prohibit it from entering into new contracts in the event that a breach of duty could endanger the interests of customers.
The amendment is also intended to adjust the financing of the mountain service.
The Ministry for Regional Development will determine the amount of subsidy to the mountain service based on its application, which will be submitted by the end of April for the following year.
The application will include a report on the use of state money in the past year, a financial plan for spending and an outlook for the next two years.
According to the association, the proponent of the law did not understand the situation, what will happen if the insurance company terminates the CK contract.
She will not be allowed to organize tours, and clients who bought the tour before the cancellation of the insurance will lose it, according to the association.
In such a case, the CK will suffer a significant loss and may even go bankrupt, even though its economy was in good condition.
One of the ways travel agencies can cope with such a situation is to sue the state for compensation.
Another option will be to go abroad and take advantage of much softer conditions abroad, and then we will only act as agencies in our market, said the vice-chairman of the association, Jan Papež.
According to him, the draft amendment also includes the institution of a bank guarantee, but it is so ill-thought-out that it cannot be implemented in practice at all, since the bank guarantee cannot be for an unlimited amount.
In addition, according to the association, changing the current practice is de facto unnecessary.
In two years&#39; time, due to the new EU directive, the entire law will have to be revised again.
A total of 942 active insured travel agencies are now operating on the Czech market.
This year, only three CCs ended their activities.
Domestic travel agencies sell tours worth roughly twenty billion CZK per year.
