Xi calls for opening up the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with governance reform on Tuesday.
&quot;China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies,&quot; he said regarding the 16th meeting of the Central Leading Group for Deepening Comprehensive Reform.
Promoting opening-up in nascent reforms will add new impetus and vitality, and also provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The leadership group adopted a series of directives, including the negative list of regulatory market access, the relaxation of border control policies, the support of state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital and the reorganization of the registration residency system.
The statement said a negative list would be drawn up to identify sectors and businesses that are off limits for investment.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through test programs.
The move is significant as it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls on the powers it delegates to firms and ensure that firms themselves decide how to run their businesses.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled industry, more areas will be opened up to private investment.
&quot;The government will not change its foreign investment policy and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services,&quot; the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a &quot;green card,&quot; thanks to the optimization of requirements and the simplification of the application process.
Ensuring the rights of lawyers to practice and developing professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at the meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Premier Li Keqiang and senior officials Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
New wards may be created in the Karlovy Vary Region.
According to the deputy governor of the Karlovy Vary Region, Jakub Pánik (ČSSD), the current capacity of the inpatient departments of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient, and partial adjustments should be made based on an agreement between the departments of individual hospitals.
However, there are also opportunities to expand care in the region.
For example, one-day surgery centers could be established in surgical departments, where procedures in surgical fields that do not require hospitalization longer than 24 hours would be performed according to the set concept.
In which specific hospitals there should be workplaces focused on one-day surgery, it is not yet clear.
A laser center with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases could be created at the skin department of the Karlovy Vary hospital.
The concept also recommended the establishment of an apallic center that would care for patients with cerebral palsy who are in a vegetative state.
Such a center should be established centrally and should be an integral part of the anesthesia-resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such equipment in Ostrov Hospital, where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity that appears to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary Region are follow-up care beds, especially Léčeben beds for long-term patients (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and, above all, should be closely related to acute care beds.
Part of this facility should function as rehabilitation beds and part as classic LDN beds, the concept recommends.
As he points out, follow-up care beds are mainly missing in the Karlovy Vary hospital.
Abandoned buildings after centralization could be used there.
Last but not least, in the Karlovy Vary region, there are no social health beds focusing on the treatment of Alzheimer&#39;s disease.
There is a shortage of these beds in the entire country, so it could also serve as a so-called Alzheimer&#39;s center for other regions.
According to the recommendation, hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-up beds, for which funds from European subsidies will be released.
&quot;These are beds that will follow the fields of superspecialized care and will create a space for transferring patients after surgery, for example, after cardiac surgery, neurosurgery, transplantation or other procedures,&quot; describes the regional concept of inpatient care.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.
